Coronavirus guidance is being updated.
Read what you can and cannot do

The Sudanese authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Sudan, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
The Sudanese authorities have closed all external borders. It is no longer possible to enter Sudan by road, sea or air. Cargo and humanitarian flights are exempted but crew must observe strict guidelines.
On 16 March 2020, the Sudanese Civil Aviation Authority closed all airports to international commercial passenger airlines.
Visas
We are urgently seeking guidance from the Sudanese authorities on the impact of the flight suspension on British Nationals whose visas or residency permits have expired or are due to expire.
Local measures
The Sudanese authorities have imposed a 24/7 lockdown in Khartoum state, which remains in place until 19 May. Curfews remain in effect throughout the rest of the country, enforced by the police and armed forces. You should check the curfew times for the state in which you are located. You should observe the lockdown and the curfew. An Emergency Order has been signed permitting police and armed forces to fine and imprison people who break curfew. You should strictly observe curfew times.
The lockdown in Khartoum State means that:
All individuals must remain at home. There are exemptions for emergency and essential workers.
Public and private gatherings are banned.
The bridges across the Nile will be closed.
People may leave home between 6am and 1pm to shop for essential items in their neighbourhood.
All public departments and institutions remain closed with the exception of core institutions including security agencies, hospitals and pharmacies.
All private companies, shops and stores are closed, with the exception of bakeries, supermarkets and haulage companies.
Penalties
The Sudanese authorities are strict in enforcing restrictions on movement within Khartoum state. You should only leave home in exceptional circumstances â€“ for example going to supermarkets or pharmacies for essential items, or to access medical care. You should comply with all local restrictions introduced by the Sudanese authorities.
Internal flights and all bus services between States have been suspended until further notice.
You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
Further information
If you are in need of urgent help, please contact the British Embassy in Khartoum or call +249 156 77 55 00.
If you are vulnerable with health issues, an older person, or will be travelling with young children, you can call +249 156 77 55 00 and follow the options for consular assistance. The numbers are available 24/7.
If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Sudanese Embassy.
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
You can find more information about cases in Sudan on the TravelHealthPro country page.
Sign up for travel advice alerts and the British Embassy Facebook and Twitter pages for updates.
